<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-05-08T05:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-05-08T05:00:00-05:00" n="636" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d636">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 E.W./5–845: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Kennan</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-05-08T13:00:00+03:00">May 8,
                                    1945—1 p.m.</date>
                                <lb/> [Received May 8—7:50 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>1496. Role of Allied armies in final stages of war continues to receive
                            most inconspicuous treatment in Moscow press whereas role of Red Army is
                            prominently featured. For the past week there has been no more than
                            passing editorial reference to military achievements of Allied armies in
                            the flood of articles concerning fall of Berlin and other Red Army
                            triumphs.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Kennan</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>